# .trivyignore — DataForge dependency-vulnerability scan exception file
# (GA-SECURITY-CHECKLIST item 13; security-architecture.md §13.1, SEC-DEP-4, TM-7).
#
# This file is consumed by the `dependency-scan` CI job (.github/workflows/ci.yaml),
# which runs `trivy fs` over the repo and FAILS the build on any HIGH/CRITICAL
# advisory in a backend (uv.lock / pyproject.toml) or frontend (package-lock.json)
# dependency. It is the single, version-controlled, tunable waiver list — the gate
# stays strict by default and exceptions are explicit, reviewable, and time-boxed.
#
# POLICY (item 13: "dependency-exception file contains no expired entries"):
#   * One CVE id per line (e.g. CVE-2024-12345). Blank lines and `#` comments allowed.
#   * EVERY entry MUST carry, in a preceding comment block:
#       - the package + why the advisory does not apply / is accepted,
#       - a tracking link (issue/PR),
#       - an EXPIRES: YYYY-MM-DD date (the time-box).
#   * An entry past its EXPIRES date is an "expired entry" and is a GA blocker per
#     the checklist — remove it (and fix the dep) or consciously re-justify + extend.
#   * Advisories with NO upstream fix are NOT listed here: the job already runs with
#     `ignore-unfixed: true`, so unpatchable upstream CVEs do not gate and need no
#     waiver. This file is only for *fixable* HIGH/CRITICAL findings we are
#     deliberately deferring for a bounded window.
#
# Format example (keep commented until a real waiver is needed):
#   # CVE-2025-00000 — <package>@<version>: <one-line justification>.
#   #   Tracking: <issue/PR url>
#   #   EXPIRES: 2026-09-01
#   CVE-2025-00000
#
# --- Active waivers ---
# (none — the gate is fully strict; add justified, time-boxed entries above as needed.)
